## OUTDOOR BLINDS KNOWLEDGE BASE

The following is the complete Lidgard Shades Outdoor Blinds FAQ. Use this as your sole source of product knowledge when answering customer questions.

---

Outdoor Blinds FAQ
Lidgard Shades - A practical guide for customers considering outdoor blinds for an existing outdoor area.

This FAQ has been prepared for homeowners and property owners looking at outdoor blinds for patios, pergolas, verandas, decks, and other covered outdoor spaces. It covers common questions around privacy, mesh fabrics, clear PVC, Ziptrak blinds, operation, weather protection, sizing, and suitability for New Zealand conditions.

Frequently Asked Questions

1. What are outdoor blinds?
Outdoor blinds are exterior screening systems designed to enclose or partially screen an outdoor living area. They can help reduce glare, filter sunlight, improve privacy, and add protection from wind and light rain. Depending on the material and system you choose, outdoor blinds can make an existing patio or pergola feel more comfortable and usable through more of the year.

2. Can outdoor blinds be added to an existing outdoor area?
Yes. In many cases, outdoor blinds can be fitted to an existing pergola, veranda, patio, alfresco area, or covered deck. The main thing we check is whether there is a suitable structure to fix the blind system to, along with the size of the opening, the way the space is used, and how exposed it is to wind and weather.

3. What are the main benefits of outdoor blinds?
The main benefits are better shade, reduced glare, more privacy, and more protection from the weather. Outdoor blinds can also help define an outdoor room, make a space feel more sheltered, and allow you to use an area for longer periods during the day and across more seasons.

4. Do outdoor blinds help with privacy?
Yes. Outdoor blinds are a popular way to create privacy from neighbours, nearby foot traffic, or adjacent outdoor spaces. Mesh blinds are often a good choice when you want privacy during the day while still letting in filtered light and airflow. The amount of privacy depends on the fabric openness and the lighting conditions.

5. Do outdoor blinds block the sun and reduce glare?
Yes. Mesh style outdoor blinds are designed to filter harsh sunlight and reduce glare while still keeping the space light and open. This can make an outdoor area more comfortable for dining, entertaining, or relaxing, especially on the western or northern sides of a home where afternoon sun can be strong.

6. Do outdoor blinds protect against wind and rain?
Yes, they can help, but the level of protection depends on the blind system and material. Track guided systems such as Ziptrak are designed to create a more enclosed barrier at the sides, which helps reduce gaps. Mesh can cut wind and light weather exposure, while clear PVC is generally the better option when stronger wind and rain protection is the priority.

7. What is the difference between mesh blinds and clear PVC blinds?
Mesh blinds are made to filter light, reduce glare, and allow airflow, while clear PVC blinds are designed for visibility and stronger weather protection. Mesh gives a softer screened effect and is often chosen for privacy and shade. Clear PVC remains see through and is often chosen when you want to keep your view while creating more shelter from wind, rain, dust, and debris.

8. Which option is better for privacy, mesh or PVC?
For daytime privacy, mesh is usually the better option because it creates a screened barrier from the outside while still allowing outward visibility from within the space. Clear PVC does not provide the same privacy because it is transparent. If privacy is one of the main goals, mesh is often the first option to look at.

9. Which option is better if I want to keep my view?
If keeping your view is the main priority, clear PVC is often the best fit because it is designed to remain transparent. Mesh also allows visibility through the blind, but it has a filtered look rather than a fully clear finish. The right choice comes down to whether you value full visibility more than airflow or privacy.

10. Do mesh blinds still allow airflow?
Yes. One of the advantages of mesh outdoor blinds is that they still allow airflow through the space. This helps keep the area feeling like an outdoor environment while reducing the impact of direct sun, glare, and breezy conditions. The amount of airflow depends on the fabric openness level.

11. Do clear PVC blinds still let in light?
Yes. Clear PVC blinds let in light while also maintaining visibility through the blind. They are often used where people want to enclose an outdoor area without losing the outlook. Because the material creates a more enclosed barrier, it is often chosen for spaces where comfort in cooler or windier conditions is important.

12. What is a Ziptrak blind?
Ziptrak is a track guided outdoor blind system. Instead of relying on straps, zips, chains, or cords at the sides, the blind runs within a side track system. This helps create a cleaner look, smoother operation, and better edge retention than many standard outdoor blind systems.

13. How is Ziptrak different from a standard outdoor roller blind?
A standard outdoor roller blind usually rolls down and is then secured in place. A Ziptrak blind uses a side track system that guides the blind as it moves, helping it stay retained within the tracks. This design reduces side gaps, improves the finish, and makes the blind easier to stop and position at different heights.

14. Do Ziptrak blinds have gaps at the sides?
They are designed to reduce the side gaps that are common with many traditional outdoor blinds. That tighter edge detail helps improve shelter from wind, light rain, dust, and insects. Exact sealing performance will still depend on the structure, the opening, and the way the system is installed.

15. Can a Ziptrak blind be stopped at any height?
Yes. One of the key features of the Ziptrak system is that the blind can be left at different heights rather than only fully open or fully closed. This gives you more control over shade, privacy, airflow, and visibility throughout the day.

16. Are Ziptrak blinds available in manual and motorised options?
Yes. Outdoor blinds can be supplied in manual or motorised options, depending on the system and material selected. Ziptrak offers both manual and electric operation, while manual crank operated roller shade systems are also available for some applications.

17. Are motorised blinds worth it?
For many people, yes. Motorisation adds convenience, especially for larger blinds, multiple blinds, or blinds installed in harder to reach places. It can make day to day use easier and can be a good option for households wanting quick operation at the touch of a button.

18. Can Ziptrak blinds be motorised with both mesh and PVC?
Not always. Based on the supplied product information, motorisation is available with Sunscreen Mesh in the Ziptrak range. If you are considering clear PVC, it is best to confirm the exact operating options for your preferred size and layout during the quoting stage.

19. How big can outdoor blinds be?
Maximum sizes depend on the blind system, material, and site conditions. Lidgard Shades' roller shade information notes sizes up to 4500mm width and 4800mm span for that system. The Ziptrak catalogue states custom sizes up to 6m wide and up to 3.5m high, subject to project requirements. Wider openings may sometimes need a removable or fixed post depending on the design.

20. Are there size restrictions for outdoor blinds?
Yes. Every outdoor blind system has practical size limits based on performance, wind loading, operation, and the strength of the structure it is fixed to. Large openings can often still be achieved, but they may require heavier duty components, different operating options, or added structural support.

21. Can outdoor blinds be custom made to suit my space?
Yes. Outdoor blinds are generally custom measured and made to suit the exact opening. This is important for getting the right fit, the right level of protection, and a clean finished look. It also allows the blind to be matched to the way your outdoor area is used.

22. What colours and finishes are available?
There is usually a good range of fabric and hardware colours available. Mesh fabrics come in a range of colours and openness levels, and Ziptrak aluminium componentry is available in several standard colours with powder coating options available for broader colour matching. This makes it easier to complement an existing pergola, joinery, or outdoor structure.

23. What is a pelmet, and do I need one?
A pelmet is the cover section at the top of the blind system that helps hide and protect the rolled fabric and operating components. It can improve the finished appearance of the blind and help protect the system from weather exposure. Whether you need one will depend on the system you choose and the look you want.

24. Are outdoor blinds suitable for coastal properties?
They can be, provided the right materials and hardware are used. Lidgard Shades notes the use of aluminium framing and stainless steel fixings for durability, including in coastal environments. Site exposure is still important, so coastal projects should always be assessed carefully for wind, corrosion, and salt exposure.

25. Can outdoor blinds help make an outdoor area feel like another room?
Yes. This is one of the most common reasons people install them. Outdoor blinds can help define the edges of a space, make it feel more sheltered, and improve comfort enough that the area gets used more often. Clear PVC in particular is often chosen where people want to create a more enclosed outdoor room while still keeping the outlook.

26. Are outdoor blinds easy to operate?
Yes. Modern outdoor blind systems are designed for simple day to day use. Depending on the product, operation may be by hand, by crank handle, or by motor. Ziptrak is designed for smooth guided movement, and manual systems can also be straightforward when correctly sized and installed.

27. Are outdoor blinds easy to clean and maintain?
Generally, yes. Outdoor blinds are made for exterior use and are designed to be durable and practical. Mesh fabrics are typically low maintenance and do not require frequent cleaning. Clear PVC also needs regular care to keep it looking its best, and the best cleaning method should follow the product care guidance for the material selected.

28. Will outdoor blinds completely weatherproof an outdoor space?
Not in every case. Outdoor blinds can significantly improve shelter and comfort, but they do not turn every outdoor area into a fully sealed interior room. The level of weather protection will depend on the blind type, side detail, structure, and exposure to wind. A site specific assessment helps determine what level of enclosure is realistic.

29. Can outdoor blinds be installed on large commercial or hospitality spaces?
Yes. Outdoor blinds are used in homes as well as in commercial settings such as cafes, restaurants, schools, and other outdoor gathering spaces. Large openings can often be accommodated with the right system, but commercial projects need careful planning around size, usage, access, and durability.

30. How do I choose the right outdoor blind for my space?
The best choice usually comes down to your main priority. If you want privacy, filtered light, and airflow, mesh is often the better option. If you want to keep your view and improve shelter from wind and rain, clear PVC may be better. If you want a cleaner, more secure track guided system, Ziptrak is a strong option. The right answer depends on the size of the opening, how exposed it is, and how you want to use the space.

Important note
Outdoor blind suitability, sizes, operating options, and material recommendations can vary from project to project. Existing structure, wind exposure, opening size, and the intended use of the space all affect the final recommendation. A site measure and consultation is the best way to confirm the right solution for your outdoor area.

